post_text:
Tonight the Keokuk Chiefs football team will be playing Burlington at Calvert Stadium. Please remember that face coverings are required for everyone in the stadium at all times until you are safely socially distanced in your seat. Families may sit together, but please remain socially distant from others. Student Sections will require face coverings for both teams.

Bleachers will be marked off to maintain social distancing. The hills beside the bleachers will also be available for seating.

Students PreK through 8th grade MUST remain seated with an adult.

Please adhere to these rules so that we will be able to continue allowing public attendance at our athletic events.

Katie Geltz
September 9 at 5:14 PM ·

I love how many people are supportive of teachers and are understanding of the difficulties we’re facing...

But I need to show appreciation for the custodial staff at Keokuk High School. Our building has always been maintained and clean but since covid-19 came around the diligence they’ve used in keeping our environment safe is so amazing.

So to the custodial and maintenance staff-
We see you constantly on the move.
We see you providing us with supplies.
We see you taking extra care in making sure surfaces have been cleaned and sanitized.
We see you shouldering more of the responsibilities so we have more time to work with the kids.
We see you.
Thank you.

post_text:
We had a great first week of school! Thank you all for following our health and safety protocols for face coverings, frequent hand washing, social distancing and sanitizing.

Although the COVID numbers in the county have been increasing, the numbers at KCSD remain low.

We have no new positive student cases to report. The previous positive student has not attended school yet and we are hoping for a full recovery.

The COVID related staff numbers are as follows:

HS - No new positives; 2 awaiting test results and are quarantining.

MS - 1 new positive who is quarantining.

Nutrition - 1 new quarantine due to possible exposure.

Transportation - 1 previous positive has recovered; 1 awaiting test results and quarantining; one new quarantine due to possible exposure.

This is the most current information as of 8/30/20.

As a reminder, please do not send your child to school if they have a fever or exhibit any COVID related symptoms.

Thank you for staying safe and following our district health protocols.

post_text: CONGRATULATIONS!!!
shared_text:
K-Pride at Keokuk High School
April 28 at 5:45 PM ·

On April 23rd, the State Science and Technology Fair hosted their virtual awards ceremony. This year, the fair was open to high school students (due to COVID-19, there was not a Middle School portion). Prior to the ceremony, students submitted a picture of their science fair board/presentation, as well as a 10 minute (or less) video presentation sharing information about their research project they conducted. There were 14 categories that students competed in, judges selected the 1st and 2nd place project for each of the 14 categories. From Keokuk High School: team Carson Sargent and Anthony Potratz received 1st place in Behavior & Social Science, Abbie Haage was awarded 1st place in Biochemistry, Olivia Rule received 2nd place in Physics & Astronomy. We are very proud of you and all of our students that competed!!!! #KPride

shared_text:
K-Pride Hawthorne Elementary-Keokuk, IA
April 3 at 11:55 PM ·

Hello Little Chief families,

I’m sorry I’m posting this late at night but I wanted to get this information out to you as soon as I made the decision, which has been hard to make.

We’re sorry to say that we are cancelling the Parent Parade tomorrow. While we’ve all been looking forward to seeing our students, there have been some new developments locally as the COVID-19 has now spread into Lee County. Many of our staff also live in neighboring states that have made orders for residents to stay at home. It would be irresponsible on our part to encourage families and staff to travel to our schools under the new circumstances. Sorry to disappoint!

Please take care! Take precautions and practice social distancing! We miss you very much!!

Sincerely,
Mr. Marsden

**please help us in sharing this post to inform everyone of the cancellation**

post_text:
Dear KCSD Families,

At this critical time with the anticipation of school being closed until April 10, 2020 with students returning on April 13, our district wants to support our families as much as possible. All schools will be open on Thursday, March 19, from 9-4, for families to come into the buildings to pick up things including student medications, personal items, and teacher created resources to support education during the school shutdown. Please complete this form as soon as possible so we can plan for meal services at local pick-up sites to our families with all children under the age of 18. If you do not have email, please contact a building administrator for assistance.This is an ever changing situation and more details will follow as they are received. Thank you for supporting one another during these unprecedented times.

shared_text:
K-Pride at Keokuk High School
January 27 at 5:52 PM ·

The Keokuk High School Concert Band has been chosen as the 3A Concert Band for the 2020 Iowa Bandmasters Association (IBA) Conference. This is the highest achievement a concert band and band program in the state of Iowa can receive.

On January 10, our band recorded 3 pieces and submitted them to a committee of band directors from all levels and classes. Many bands submitted recordings, but only one band from each class is chosen from the entire state. This is a huge honor for this program, with Keokuk High School’s last appearance on the IBA stage being in 1995.

We are honored and excited to be selected for this prestigious opportunity and look forward to giving our concert at the conference on May 15, 2020 in Des Moines, IA!

post_text: Some folks have inquired as to the use of the middle school on Sunday afternoon by a presidential candidate for the purpose of holding a political rally. Keokuk Community School District does have a policy that allows for facility rentals by groups or individuals, so long as it does not interrupt the school day. Renting any of KCSD's facilities does require payment of a rental fee, which Senator Sanders' campaign did pay. The district does not endorse any political candidate, nor should the use of district facilities imply such.

Keokuk Vocal Music Department
October 24, 2019 at 1:54 PM ·

Alyssa Campbell and Hank Sparrow, KHS 9th graders, were recently selected for participation in the 32nd annual Opus Honor Choir Festival.

Over 2,600 students were nominated by their directors for 720 positions in the four Opus Honor Choirs. Selections were made by means of recorded audition. The 2019 Opus Honor Choirs will perform at 4:00 p.m. November 21st in C.Y. Stephens Auditorium in the Iowa State Center in Ames, Iowa. The Opus Honor Choir Festival is made possible by the Iowa Choral Directors Association, Inc.

Congratulations to Alyssa and Hank!

Over 2,600 students were nominated by their directors for 720 positions in the four Opus Honor Choirs. Selections were made by means of recorded audition. The 2019 Opus Honor Choirs will perform at 4:00 p.m. November 21st in C.Y. Stephens Auditorium in the Iowa State Center in Ames, Iowa. The Opus Honor Choir Festival is made possible by the Iowa Choral Directors Association, Inc.

Congratulations to Alyssa and Hank!

We want to thank American Idol’s Dave Pittman for coming to Keokuk High School today. A couple of important points he shared was acceptance first and then embracing the issue or change in your life. The only way to beat failure is to accept and embrace the change. That is how you overcome adversity. Dave suffers from Tourette Syndrome and when he sings you would never know it. He is a special person and living proof that you can overcome anything. #KPride

post_text:
Yesterday at Keokuk High School, it was reported that a student had created a list including names of students, for unknown purpose. As with any potential threat, we took this allegation very seriously. This was immediately investigated by school administrators and local law enforcement, property searched and no evidence of any list was found. Last night an alleged threat posted to social media was circulated widely as being created by this same student. Law enforcement has been investigating to determine the source of the original social media post. It is believed that this may quite possibly be the action of another individual outside of the district, attempting to cast suspicion on our student. This is an ongoing investigation and we are cooperating fully with law enforcement.

Thank you for your cooperation and understanding as we work together to insure a safe environment for our students.

Sincerely,
Christine Barnes
Superintendent

K-Pride Hawthorne Elementary-Keokuk, IA
September 18, 2019 at 8:15 PM ·

W.O.W. Wednesday
(Wonder of the Week)

Mrs. Ard is a wonder in the classroom! She just received a $300 grant from the Keokuk Community School Foundation to increase her thematic mentor text library. Congratulations!

Her students are doing a wonderful job meeting our little chief expectations. They have filled their classroom basket with chief change and added it to our school wide bucket, great teamwork!

For those wondering about Mrs. Ard outside the classroom, here is a small glimpse.
She has been teaching for 29 years, with 17 years in the Keokuk School District.
Everyone in her family (including her husband, all 3 children, and herself) hold degrees from WIU!
When she was in elementary school she wanted to be a comedian🙂
Some of her favorites are: reading, the color blue, spending time with family and friends, almost anything chocolate, and floating in the pool.

Keep up the great work little chief family and check back next week to see who the next W.O.W. Wednesday will feature.

The Keokuk Community School District has added two more sites for this year. Meals will be provided to all children without charge and are the same for all children. There will be no discrimination in the course of the meal service. Meals will be provided at the site and time as follows:

Dates: June 4th-August 2nd 2019 Meals served Monday-Friday. No lunch served on July 4th holiday.

Locations & Times:
- Keokuk HS Cafeteria 11:00-11:30am (starts June 4th)
- Shady Acres Mobile Home Park 12:30-1:00pm (starts June 5th)
- Keokuk Park Apts. 11:00am-12:00pm (starts June 5th)

Kids under 18 eat free. Adult meal price is $3.75.

For more information, Contact Denise Estrada or Sarah Hackett at (319) 524-1402 ext. 1021.

post_text:
Get ready for this year's Alley Cat Bicycle Rally!

An Alleycat Bicycle Rally is a form of unsanctioned street racing on bicycles created decades ago by bike messengers. Competitors combine navigation skills with raw speed to complete courses that might criss-cross a community for miles. A list of checkpoints is given out just minutes before the race and there is no set route.

3 races are available:
City to City to City (30+ miles)
The Easy Ten (10+ miles)
The Grand Meander - Family Fun Ride - Free (T-shirt NOT included)

There is a $15 registration fee & pre-registration is encouraged.
T-shirt is provided to those who pre-register by April 30, 2019.

Registration forms are available at 511 Blondeau Street, Keokuk, IA 52632, online at http://www.mainstreetkeokuk.com/2019-alley-cat-bike-rally/ or by email at director@mainstreetkeokuk.com.

Start/Finish Line is at Main Street Keokuk, Inc. office at 511 Blondeau Street. The Alleycat Bicycle Rally is a family-friendly event.

For questions, please call the Main Street Keokuk, Inc. office at 319.524.5056
